sample_data.description: Handwritten Devanagari character dataset containing grayscale images of 46 characters including consonants 'ka' to 'gya' and digits 0-9. Large-scale dataset for Devanagari script recognition.

creator.name: S. Acharya, A.K. Pant, P.K. Gyawali
creator.note: Originally created for deep learning research on Devanagari script

target_values.script: Devanagari (used for Hindi, Nepali, Marathi, etc.)

sample_data.use_case: Devanagari OCR, handwriting recognition, document digitization, multilingual text processing, educational applications
sample_data.cultural_significance: Devanagari is used by over 600 million people for languages including Hindi, Nepali, Marathi
sample_data.preprocessing: Handwritten samples collected and normalized to 32x32 grayscale images
sample_data.performance_considerations: Large dataset size, 46-way classification, handwriting variation
sample_data.advantages: Large scale dataset, balanced classes, standardized format, culturally important script
sample_data.challenges: High number of classes (46), handwriting style variations, similar looking characters
sample_data.research_applications: Deep learning for Indic scripts, multilingual OCR, transfer learning for related scripts, handwriting analysis
sample_data.related_work: Important for digitizing historical texts and modern documents in Devanagari

sample_data.description: Predict biological response of molecules from their chemical properties. Each instance represents a molecule with calculated molecular descriptors capturing characteristics like size, shape, and elemental constitution.
sample_data.creator: Boehringer Ingelheim (pharmaceutical company)
sample_data.feature_description: 1776 molecular descriptors (d1 through d1776) representing calculated properties that capture molecular characteristics including size, shape, elemental constitution, and other chemical properties. All features have been normalized.

target_values.0: Molecule did not elicit biological response

sample_data.use_case: Drug discovery, virtual screening, molecular activity prediction, chemical compound classification, pharmaceutical research and development
sample_data.data_collection: Molecular descriptors calculated from chemical structures, with experimental biological activity data
sample_data.data_characteristics: High-dimensional dataset with normalized molecular descriptors, proprietary pharmaceutical data released for competition
sample_data.challenges: Very high dimensionality (1776 features), feature interpretability limited due to proprietary nature, potential for overfitting
sample_data.advantages: Real pharmaceutical industry data, large number of molecular descriptors, pre-normalized features
sample_data.mathematical_background: Molecular descriptors capture 2D and 3D structural properties, physicochemical properties, and topological indices of molecules
sample_data.research_impact: Demonstrates application of machine learning to drug discovery and molecular property prediction
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Proprietary data with anonymized descriptors limits interpretability and reproducibility of chemical insights

sample_data.dataset_description: This dataset aims to determine which eucalyptus seedlots in various species are best for soil conservation in seasonally dry hill country of New Zealand. Data was collected from various trial sites across the North Island, measuring tree growth characteristics, survival rates, and site conditions. The utility rating indicates overall suitability for soil conservation purposes.
sample_data.dataset_source: Bruce Bulloch, New Zealand - Agricultural/Forestry research

target_variable.name: Utility
target_variable.description: Overall utility rating for soil conservation

sample_data.description: Multiple Features Dataset: Karhunen-Loève coefficients. One of six datasets describing features of handwritten numerals (0-9) extracted from Dutch utility maps. This dataset contains features from the Karhunen-Loève Transform, representing linear projections onto eigenvectors of the covariance matrix.
sample_data.creator: Robert P.W. Duin (Delft University of Technology)
sample_data.feature_description: 64 Karhunen-Loève coefficients extracted from handwritten digit images. The KLT is a linear transformation that projects the image data onto the eigenvectors of the covariance matrix, effectively performing Principal Component Analysis.
sample_data.use_case: Handwritten digit recognition for document processing, postal automation, bank check processing, and form digitization
sample_data.data_collection: Handwritten numerals extracted from a collection of Dutch utility maps, digitized in binary images
sample_data.mathematical_background: Karhunen-Loève Transform is equivalent to PCA, providing optimal linear features in terms of reconstruction error
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Dataset represents Dutch handwriting styles and may not generalize to other writing systems or cultural contexts

sample_data.description: Primate splice-junction gene sequences (DNA) for identifying boundaries between exons and introns. The StatLog version processes DNA sequences into 180 binary indicator variables representing the presence of specific nucleotides at specific positions.

creator.name: Ross King
creator.original_donors: G. Towell, M. Noordewier, and J. Shavlik

feature_description.features: 180 binary features encoding DNA sequence information, representing nucleotide patterns around splice junctions

sample_data.use_case: Gene structure prediction, splice site recognition, genomic sequence analysis, protein synthesis understanding
sample_data.preprocessing: Original sequences processed into binary features by StatLog project, encoding presence/absence of nucleotide patterns
sample_data.original_data: Raw sequences still available at UCI repository
sample_data.performance_considerations: High-dimensional binary data (180 features), relatively balanced three-class problem
sample_data.advantages: Well-studied benchmark, biological significance, processed features available
sample_data.challenges: High dimensionality, understanding feature encoding, biological interpretation
sample_data.research_applications: Sequence classification, bioinformatics, feature selection in high-dimensional spaces, pattern recognition in biological sequences
sample_data.statlog_modifications: Converted from raw sequences to 180 binary indicator variables

sample_data.description: Letter recognition dataset where the objective is to identify black-and-white rectangular pixel displays as one of the 26 capital letters in the English alphabet. Character images were based on 20 different fonts with random distortions to produce 20,000 unique stimuli. Each stimulus was converted into 16 primitive numerical attributes using statistical moments and edge counts.
sample_data.creator: David J. Slate (Odesta Corporation)
sample_data.feature_scale: All features scaled to integers from 0 through 15
sample_data.use_case: Optical character recognition (OCR) for identifying capital letters from pixel displays. Applications include document digitization, automated mail sorting, and text extraction from images.
sample_data.data_generation: Images captured at 128x128 pixels, quantized to 64 gray levels, thresholded to binary, and processed with HIPS (Hierarchical Image Processing System) extension BINATTS
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Dataset represents only capital letters in English alphabet, limiting applicability to other scripts or languages. Care should be taken when deploying in multilingual contexts.

citations.author: P. W. Frey and D. J. Slate
citations.title: Letter Recognition Using Holland-style Adaptive Classifiers

sample_data.description: Indian Liver Patient Dataset for predicting liver disease. Contains biochemical and demographic data collected from patients in North East Andhra Pradesh, India.

target_classes.name: yes
target_classes.meaning: Patient has liver disease - confirmed liver patient

target_classes.name: no
target_classes.meaning: Patient does not have liver disease - non-liver patient

sample_data.dataset_history: Collected as part of comparative study between USA and Indian liver patients. Original dataset had 583 records with 416 liver patients and 167 non-liver patients. Contains 441 male and 142 female patient records, showing gender imbalance.
sample_data.inference_notes: Dataset shows significant class imbalance with 71.4% liver patients. Gender imbalance (75.6% male) may reflect disease prevalence or sampling bias. Biochemical markers show effectiveness varies by gender, suggesting need for stratified analysis. The albumin/globulin ratio provides integrated measure of liver function. Missing values exist in some biochemical measurements.

sample_data.description: Telecommunications customer churn dataset containing telephony account features and usage patterns to predict whether customers will switch providers. Originally used in 'Discovering Knowledge in Data: An Introduction to Data Mining'.
sample_data.original_source: BigML, supposedly from UCI (not found there)

creator.note: Unknown original creator, distributed via PMLB

class_distribution.note: Imbalanced dataset typical of real-world churn scenarios

sample_data.use_case: Customer retention, churn prediction, targeted marketing, customer lifetime value optimization, proactive retention campaigns
sample_data.business_context: Retaining existing customers is more cost-effective than acquiring new ones
sample_data.preprocessing: Features include derived charge amounts from usage, area codes as categorical
sample_data.performance_considerations: Class imbalance (14% churn rate), need for cost-sensitive learning or resampling techniques
sample_data.advantages: Real business problem, clear features, actionable insights possible
sample_data.challenges: Imbalanced classes, temporal aspects not captured, regional variations
sample_data.research_applications: Binary classification, imbalanced learning, customer analytics, feature importance for business insights
sample_data.evaluation_metrics: Recall/sensitivity crucial for identifying churners, precision-recall trade-offs, cost-sensitive evaluation
sample_data.business_value: Even 1% reduction in churn can lead to significant revenue retention

citations.reference: Used in 'Discovering Knowledge in Data: An Introduction to Data Mining' by Daniel T. Larose

sample_data.description: Used in decision tree induction for mitigating process delays known as 'cylinder bands' in rotogravure printing. Dataset contains attributes describing printing conditions and processes to predict whether banding defects will occur.

creator.name: Bob Evans
creator.methodology: Machine learning approach where learning system generates rules rather than direct expert elicitation

sample_data.use_case: Process control in rotogravure printing, defect prediction, quality assurance, preventive maintenance
sample_data.industrial_context: Rotogravure printing process optimization to reduce cylinder banding delays
sample_data.preprocessing: Handle missing values (shown as '?' in dataset), mixed numeric and categorical features
sample_data.performance_considerations: Missing values present, combination of process parameters and material properties
sample_data.advantages: Real industrial application, practical manufacturing problem, diverse feature types
sample_data.challenges: Missing values, domain expertise required, complex interactions between printing parameters
sample_data.research_applications: Industrial defect prediction, decision tree learning with missing values, manufacturing process optimization
sample_data.methodology_note: Exemplifies approach where machine learning system generates rules rather than direct expert knowledge elicitation

sample_data.dataset_description: This dataset contains texture features extracted from Brodatz album images using fourth-order modified moments for characterizing natural micro-textures. The dataset includes 11 different texture classes (Grass lawn, Pressed calf leather, Handmade paper, Raffia looped to a high pile, Cotton canvas, Pigskin, Beach sand, Oriental straw cloth, Oriental grass fiber cloth) with 500 instances per class, totaling 5,500 instances. Each instance is described by 40 attributes representing fourth-order modified moments estimated in four orientations (0°, 45°, 90°, 135°).
sample_data.dataset_source: Brodatz texture album, statistical texture analysis research

target_variable.name: class
target_variable.description: Texture class labels corresponding to different Brodatz texture types

sample_data.description: Speaker-independent recognition of eleven steady-state vowels of British English. Features are derived from spectral analysis of vowel sounds, with contextual information about speaker gender and identity.
sample_data.creator: David Deterding (Cambridge University)
sample_data.use_case: Vowel recognition systems, speech recognition, phonetic analysis, speaker-independent speech processing, accent detection
sample_data.dataset_characteristics: 15 speakers (8 male, 7 female) each pronouncing 11 vowels in 'h*d' context, 6 utterances per vowel per speaker
sample_data.data_collection: Steady-state vowels extracted from speakers saying words in 'h_d' context (e.g., 'heed', 'hid', 'head')
sample_data.signal_processing: 10-dimensional feature vectors derived from spectral analysis, likely including formant frequencies
sample_data.challenges: Limited number of speakers, British English specific, steady-state vowels only (not continuous speech)
sample_data.mathematical_background: Features likely based on formant analysis and spectral characteristics of vowel sounds
sample_data.advantages: Balanced dataset, well-controlled recording conditions, classic benchmark for vowel recognition
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Limited to British English speakers, may not generalize to other accents or languages

sample_data.description: Pima Indians Diabetes Database for predicting onset of diabetes mellitus. Contains diagnostic measurements from female patients of Pima Indian heritage near Phoenix, Arizona, USA.
sample_data.dataset_history: Collected from a larger database with constraints: all patients are females at least 21 years old of Pima Indian heritage. The Pima population has the highest reported prevalence of diabetes globally. Original ADAP algorithm achieved 76% sensitivity and specificity using 576 training instances.
sample_data.inference_notes: Dataset contains 768 instances with 500 negative and 268 positive cases (34.9% diabetes rate). All patients from homogeneous population reduces confounding variables. The diabetes pedigree function synthesizes family history into a single genetic risk score. Zero values in some fields (e.g., glucose, blood pressure) likely represent missing data rather than actual zeros, requiring careful preprocessing.

sample_data.description: Machine learning dataset for automated theorem proving. Predicts which of five heuristics will give the fastest proof when used by a first-order prover, with a sixth option to decline attempting a proof if the theorem is too difficult.
sample_data.source: UCI Machine Learning Repository / University of Cambridge
sample_data.creator: James P. Bridge, Sean B. Holden, Lawrence C. Paulson (University of Cambridge Computer Laboratory)
sample_data.feature_description: Mixture of static and dynamic features derived from theorems to be proved, including structural properties, complexity measures, and syntactic characteristics of first-order logic formulas

target_values.6: Theorem too difficult - decline to prove

sample_data.use_case: Automated theorem proving, heuristic selection for proof search, machine learning for mathematical reasoning, optimization of theorem provers
sample_data.data_collection: Features extracted from first-order logic theorems, with performance data from running different heuristics on a theorem prover
sample_data.mathematical_background: First-order logic theorem proving using resolution-based methods with different search heuristics
sample_data.challenges: Complex feature engineering required, difficulty in capturing logical structure, heuristic performance may vary with prover implementation
sample_data.advantages: Enables intelligent heuristic selection, improves theorem prover efficiency, bridges machine learning and automated reasoning
sample_data.research_impact: Demonstrates application of machine learning to improve automated reasoning systems
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Automated reasoning systems should be transparent about their limitations and not replace human mathematical verification for critical applications

sample_data.description: Encrypted stock market data from Numerai hedge fund tournament. Features are cleaned, regularized and encrypted global equity data with anonymized feature names. Part of Numerai's crowd-sourced hedge fund competition.

creator.name: Numerai
creator.note: Features are encrypted/anonymized for proprietary reasons

sample_data.use_case: Quantitative trading, market prediction, crowd-sourced hedge fund strategies, financial machine learning
sample_data.preprocessing: Data is pre-cleaned, regularized, and encrypted by Numerai
sample_data.performance_considerations: Cannot interpret features directly, must rely on statistical patterns
sample_data.advantages: Real financial data, large dataset, professionally cleaned, unique crowd-sourcing approach
sample_data.challenges: Feature interpretation impossible, black-box modeling only, proprietary nature
sample_data.research_applications: Financial prediction, ensemble methods, feature engineering on encrypted data, transfer learning
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Part of innovative crowd-sourced hedge fund model, democratizing quantitative finance

sample_data.description: Landsat satellite image dataset consisting of multi-spectral values of pixels in 3x3 neighborhoods. The database contains spectral data from four digital images of the same scene in different spectral bands (two visible, two near-infrared). The task is to predict the soil type classification of the central pixel based on multi-spectral values.
sample_data.creator: Ashwin Srinivasan, Department of Statistics and Data Modeling, University of Strathclyde
sample_data.use_case: Land cover classification from satellite imagery. Applications include agricultural monitoring, environmental assessment, urban planning, and natural resource management. Useful for automated analysis of large-scale geographical areas.
sample_data.data_generation: Landsat Multi-Spectral Scanner (MSS) imagery with spatial resolution of 80m x 80m per pixel. Sub-area of 82x100 pixels extracted from larger 2340x3380 pixel scene. Four spectral bands captured simultaneously.
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Satellite imagery classification should consider privacy implications when applied to inhabited areas. Environmental monitoring applications should be used responsibly to support sustainable land use practices.

sample_data.description: Nomao is a dataset for data deduplication of place information. It contains features comparing two places (spots) collected from multiple web sources to determine if they refer to the same physical location. The dataset was enriched during the Nomao Challenge at ECML-PKDD 2012 conference.
sample_data.source: UCI Machine Learning Repository / Nomao Labs
sample_data.creator: Laurent Candillier and Vincent Lemaire (Nomao Labs)
sample_data.use_case: Identifying duplicate place entries in location-based services, search engines, and business directories. Essential for data quality in mapping applications and local search.
sample_data.active_learning_context: Dataset was specifically designed for active learning research, demonstrating how to efficiently label data for deduplication tasks
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Place data may contain business information that could be sensitive. Deduplication accuracy is crucial for fair representation of businesses in search results and maps.

sample_data.description: Remote sensing dataset for detecting diseased trees (Japanese oak wilt and Japanese pine wilt) in Quickbird satellite imagery. Contains spectral and texture features from image segments with highly imbalanced classes.
sample_data.use_case: Forest health monitoring, disease detection in vegetation, precision forestry, environmental conservation, satellite image analysis

dataset_splits.note: Testing set from stratified random sample with segmentation scale 15

sample_data.data_collection: Image segments generated by segmenting pansharpened Quickbird imagery. Segments contain both spectral information from multispectral bands and texture information from panchromatic band.
sample_data.preprocessing: Image segmentation applied to create homogeneous regions, feature extraction from each segment including spectral means and texture metrics
sample_data.performance_considerations: Extreme class imbalance requires specialized techniques (SMOTE, cost-sensitive learning, anomaly detection approaches)
sample_data.advantages: Real-world remote sensing application, high-quality satellite data, important environmental monitoring use case
sample_data.challenges: Severe class imbalance (98.5% vs 1.5%), small number of positive examples, generalization to other forest types/diseases
sample_data.research_applications: Imbalanced classification, remote sensing analysis, environmental monitoring, precision agriculture/forestry
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Environmental conservation application, potential for automated forest health monitoring to support sustainability efforts

sample_data.description: Expression levels of 77 proteins measured in the cerebral cortex of control and Down syndrome (trisomy) mice. Mice were exposed to context fear conditioning to assess associative learning, with some receiving memantine treatment.
sample_data.creator: <list with 3 items>
sample_data.feature_description: 77 protein expression levels measured in nuclear fraction of cortex. Each protein name is followed by '_n' indicating nuclear fraction measurement. Values represent expression levels detected through reverse phase protein array (RPPA).
sample_data.use_case: Biomarker discovery for Down syndrome, understanding learning deficits, drug efficacy assessment, protein expression analysis in neurological disorders
sample_data.research_objectives: Identify protein subsets discriminant between classes, understand molecular basis of learning deficits in Down syndrome, evaluate memantine as potential treatment

data_characteristics.independence: Each measurement can be considered independent
data_characteristics.missing_data: Some technical artifacts resulted in missing values

sample_data.advantages: Real biological data, important medical application, multiple experimental conditions, protein-level measurements
sample_data.challenges: Missing values due to technical artifacts, relatively small sample size per class, complex interactions between proteins
sample_data.biomedical_significance: First dataset to assess pharmacotherapy efficacy for Down syndrome cognitive deficits, potential for identifying therapeutic targets
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Animal research conducted under appropriate protocols, aimed at understanding and treating human genetic disorder

sample_data.description: The bank marketing dataset is related to direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls to convince clients to subscribe to a bank term deposit. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required. The dataset includes client demographic data, campaign information, and socio-economic indicators.
sample_data.creator: Paulo Cortez, Sérgio Moro

target_values.yes: Client subscribed to a term deposit
target_values.no: Client did not subscribe to a term deposit

sample_data.use_case: Predicting whether a client will subscribe to a term deposit based on direct marketing campaign data. Useful for optimizing marketing strategies, resource allocation, and improving campaign effectiveness.
sample_data.ethical_considerations: The dataset contains personal demographic information and should be used responsibly. Care should be taken to avoid discriminatory practices based on age, marital status, or education level. The 'duration' feature should be excluded for realistic predictive models as it's only known after the call.

sample_data.description: Steel plates fault detection dataset for identifying surface defects in stainless steel plates. The data consists of 27 geometric features describing defect shapes and their outlines, used to classify 7 types of surface defects in steel manufacturing.

creator.name: Semeion Research Center
creator.affiliation: Semeion, Research Center of Sciences of Communication, Rome, Italy
creator.note: Data was commissioned by Centro Sviluppo Materiali (Italy)

sample_data.use_case: Automated defect detection in steel manufacturing, quality control systems, industrial inspection, surface defect classification
sample_data.preprocessing: Geometric features extracted from defect regions, feature engineering including logarithmic and sigmoid transformations
sample_data.performance_considerations: Multi-class classification with imbalanced classes, Other_Faults being the dominant class
sample_data.advantages: Real industrial dataset, comprehensive geometric features, important manufacturing application
sample_data.challenges: Class imbalance, confidential nature of some feature details, need for domain expertise to interpret features
sample_data.research_applications: Industrial defect detection, multi-class classification, manufacturing quality control, pattern recognition in industrial settings

sample_data.description: MADELON is an artificial dataset created for the NIPS 2003 feature selection challenge. Data points are grouped in 32 clusters placed on the vertices of a five-dimensional hypercube and randomly labeled +1 or -1. The dataset contains 5 informative features, 15 redundant features (linear combinations of the informative features), and 480 distractor features with no predictive power. The order of features and patterns were randomized.
sample_data.creator: Isabelle Guyon
sample_data.use_case: Feature selection challenge to test algorithms' ability to identify relevant features among many irrelevant ones in a highly non-linear, multivariate problem
sample_data.ethical_considerations: As an artificial dataset, there are no direct ethical concerns. It serves as a benchmark for feature selection algorithms.

sample_data.description: Car Evaluation Database derived from a hierarchical decision model for evaluating cars based on their overall acceptability. The model evaluates cars according to price characteristics (buying price and maintenance cost) and technical characteristics (comfort and safety features).
sample_data.use_case: Car evaluation, consumer decision support, multi-criteria decision making, preference learning, product recommendation
sample_data.preprocessing: None required - categorical data in standard format, ordinal variables stored as ordered factors
sample_data.performance_considerations: Highly imbalanced classes with 70% in unacceptable category, ordinal nature of features
sample_data.advantages: Complete coverage of attribute space, well-defined hierarchical structure, no missing values, clear decision model
sample_data.challenges: Severe class imbalance, small number of positive examples (good/vgood), discrete feature space
sample_data.research_applications: Multi-class classification, ordinal classification, decision tree learning, rule-based systems, preference learning, imbalanced classification

sample_data.description: ISOLET (Isolated Letter Speech Recognition) dataset. 150 subjects spoke the name of each letter of the alphabet twice, generating 52 training examples from each speaker. Captures acoustic features for speech recognition tasks.
sample_data.creator: <list with 2 items>

donor.name: Tom Dietterich
donor.affiliation: Department of Computer Science, Oregon State University

sample_data.feature_description: 617 acoustic features including spectral coefficients, contour features, sonorant features, pre-sonorant features, and post-sonorant features. All attributes are continuous real-valued scaled into the range -1.0 to 1.0.

instances_per_class.note: 3 examples are missing due to recording difficulties

sample_data.use_case: Automatic speech recognition, speaker-independent letter recognition, speech processing research, acoustic modeling
sample_data.data_collection: 150 subjects (grouped into sets of 30 speakers each) spoke the name of each letter of the alphabet twice in a controlled environment
sample_data.advantages: Good domain for testing scaling abilities of algorithms, noisy perceptual task, speaker-independent evaluation possible
sample_data.challenges: High dimensionality (617 features), computational complexity for some algorithms (e.g., C4.5 slower than backpropagation)
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Dataset represents English alphabet pronunciation primarily from US speakers, may not generalize to other accents or languages

sample_data.description: Balance Scale Weight & Distance Database generated to model psychological experimental results. Each example represents a balance scale scenario with weights and distances on both sides. The task is to predict whether the scale tips left, tips right, or remains balanced based on the physics principle of torque.
sample_data.creator: Generated to model experiments by Siegler, R. S. (1976), donated by Tim Hume
sample_data.physics_rule: Class is determined by comparing (left-weight * left-distance) vs (right-weight * right-distance). If left product is greater, class is L. If right product is greater, class is R. If equal, class is B.

target_values.L: Balance scale tips to the left
target_values.R: Balance scale tips to the right

sample_data.use_case: Modeling cognitive development and understanding how children learn physical principles. Used to study machine learning approaches to cognitive modeling and rule learning.
sample_data.psychological_context: Based on Siegler's (1976) 'Three Aspects of Cognitive Development' study examining how children develop understanding of balance scale physics
sample_data.research_applications: Used in studies of rule-based learning, cognitive modeling, parallel distributed processing, and unified theories of cognition
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Synthetic dataset with no privacy concerns. Represents simplified physics model useful for educational and research purposes.

sample_data.description: Adult income dataset (Census Income). Predicts whether annual income exceeds $50K/yr based on census data extracted from the 1994 US Census database.

donor.name: Ron Kohavi
donor.affiliation: Data Mining and Visualization, Silicon Graphics

target_values.<=50K: Income less than or equal to $50,000 per year

sample_data.use_case: Income prediction, socioeconomic analysis, fairness in machine learning research, demographic studies, policy making

dataset_splits.note: Test set has slight different distribution characteristics

sample_data.data_collection: Extraction from 1994 US Census database with specific filtering conditions to ensure data quality
sample_data.preprocessing_notes: Missing values marked with '?', requires handling of categorical variables, potential for feature engineering from existing attributes
sample_data.advantages: Well-studied benchmark dataset, realistic class imbalance, mix of continuous and categorical features, useful for fairness studies
sample_data.challenges: Missing values in several attributes, imbalanced classes, potential bias in historical census data, sensitive attributes present
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Contains sensitive demographic information (race, sex, native-country), historical biases in income distribution, widely used in fairness and bias detection research

related_datasets.ACSIncome: Modern alternative from American Community Survey (2014-2018) addressing some limitations of original Adult dataset

sample_data.description: Image Segmentation dataset. Contains features extracted from 3x3 pixel regions of 7 outdoor images that were hand-segmented to create pixel classifications. Used for training algorithms to segment images into different regions.
sample_data.creator: Vision Group, University of Massachusetts
sample_data.use_case: Image segmentation, region classification, texture analysis, computer vision education, outdoor scene understanding

dataset_splits.note: Instances drawn randomly from database of 7 outdoor images

sample_data.data_collection: 7 outdoor images were manually segmented to create ground truth classification for every pixel. Features computed from 3x3 regions around each pixel.

feature_engineering.color_features: RGB raw values, excess color measures, HSV values

sample_data.advantages: Balanced classes, well-defined problem, mix of color and texture features, suitable for benchmarking
sample_data.challenges: Limited to 7 source images, small region size (3x3), outdoor scenes only
sample_data.research_applications: Texture classification, color-based segmentation, feature selection studies, multi-class classification benchmarking
sample_data.historical_significance: Early dataset in image segmentation research, widely used benchmark in 1990s-2000s
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Dataset contains only outdoor scenes, may not generalize to indoor environments or other image types

sample_data.description: The banknote authentication dataset contains features extracted from images of genuine and forged banknote specimens using Wavelet Transform tool. Data were collected from 400x400 pixel grayscale images at 660 dpi resolution taken with an industrial camera for print inspection. The dataset is used to distinguish between authentic and counterfeit banknotes.
sample_data.creator: Volker Lohweg (University of Applied Sciences, Ostwestfalen-Lippe)
sample_data.use_case: Authentication of banknotes to detect counterfeits using image processing features
sample_data.ethical_considerations: The dataset should be used responsibly to improve banknote security features and counterfeit detection systems. Misuse for creating counterfeits is illegal and unethical.

sample_data.description: Optical Recognition of Handwritten Digits dataset containing handwritten digit samples (0-9) from 43 people. Images were preprocessed from 32x32 bitmaps divided into 4x4 non-overlapping blocks, counting pixels in each block to generate 8x8 input matrices with integer values 0-16. This dimensionality reduction provides invariance to small distortions.
sample_data.creator: E. Alpaydin, C. Kaynak (Bogazici University)

feature_descriptions.input1-input64: Integer values (0-16) representing the count of 'on' pixels in each 4x4 block of the original 32x32 image, arranged in an 8x8 grid

sample_data.feature_scale: All features are integers in range 0-16
sample_data.use_case: Optical character recognition (OCR) for handwritten digit recognition. Applications include postal code reading, bank check processing, form digitization, and automated document processing.
sample_data.data_generation: Original images from preprinted forms scanned and processed using NIST preprocessing routines. 32x32 bitmaps divided into non-overlapping 4x4 blocks with pixel counting in each block.
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Dataset represents handwritten digits from a specific population (30 training, 13 test contributors). Performance may vary for different handwriting styles or populations not represented in the original sample.

sample_data.description: The Statlog Vehicle Silhouettes dataset contains features extracted from 2D silhouettes of four types of vehicles. The purpose is to classify vehicle silhouettes using shape features extracted by the HIPS (Hierarchical Image Processing System) extension BINATTS, which combines classical moment-based measures and heuristic shape descriptors.
sample_data.creator: JP Siebert (Turing Institute)
sample_data.use_case: Vehicle type classification from silhouettes for applications in traffic monitoring, automated toll systems, parking management, and security surveillance

data_collection.sets: Two sets (e2 and e3) of 60 images each per vehicle

sample_data.expected_difficulty: Bus and van expected to be easily distinguishable from cars, but distinguishing between the two car models (Saab and Opel) expected to be more challenging
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Dataset uses toy models rather than real vehicles, limiting real-world applicability. Care should be taken when generalizing to actual vehicle recognition systems.

citations.author: Siebert, JP
citations.title: Vehicle Recognition Using Rule Based Methods

sample_data.description: NASA Metrics Data Program defect dataset for software quality prediction. Contains McCabe and Halstead metrics extracted from C language modules of a real-time predictive ground system used for satellite simulations.
sample_data.source: PROMISE Software Engineering Repository / NASA MDP
sample_data.creator: NASA Metrics Data Program (Mike Chapman, Pat Callis)
sample_data.use_case: Software defect prediction, quality assurance, risk assessment, resource allocation for testing, identifying fault-prone modules

dataset_family.description: Part of NASA Metrics Data Program collection
other_datasets: CM1, PC1, PC2, PC3, PC4, PC5

sample_data.data_collection: Static code metrics extracted from C language source code using McCabe and Halstead feature extractors
sample_data.mathematical_background: McCabe metrics measure code complexity through control flow analysis. Halstead metrics estimate program difficulty through operator and operand analysis
sample_data.challenges: Severe class imbalance (80% defective), metrics from 1970s may not capture modern software complexity, single programming language
sample_data.advantages: Well-studied benchmark dataset, objective metrics from source code, large number of instances
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Metrics-based prediction should complement, not replace, human code review. Risk of over-relying on automated predictions

sample_data.description: Multiple Features Dataset: Factors. One of six datasets describing features of handwritten numerals (0-9) extracted from Dutch utility maps. sample_data.description: Pen-Based Recognition of Handwritten Digits dataset. Contains coordinate information from pen trajectories captured while writing digits 0-9 on a pressure-sensitive tablet. The data represents the dynamic movement of pen strokes rather than static images.

sample_data.feature_description: 16 features representing 8 (x,y) coordinate pairs sampled along the pen trajectory. Features are resampled spatially at regular arc-length intervals rather than temporal intervals for better alignment.
sample_data.use_case: Online handwriting recognition for pen-based interfaces, digital signature verification, tablet input systems, and educational applications
sample_data.dynamic_vs_static: Unlike static digit recognition, this dataset captures the temporal dynamics of writing, including stroke order and velocity information
sample_data.reported_accuracy: k-NN achieves 97.74% accuracy with k=1 using Euclidean distance
sample_data.experimental_notes: Spatial resampling (T=8 points) provided best trade-off between accuracy and complexity compared to T=12 or T=16
sample_data.ethical_considerations: Dataset may reflect writing styles specific to the participant pool and may not generalize across different cultures or writing systems

sample_data.description: Chess endgame dataset representing King+Rook versus King+Pawn positions. Contains 3,196 chess positions where White (with King and Rook) faces Black (with King and Pawn on a7, one square from promotion). The task is to classify whether White can force a win or if the position is drawn/lost.
sample_data.original_source: Created by Alen Shapiro in 1983 at University of Edinburgh under Donald Michie. Originally titled 'Chess End-Game -- King+Rook versus King+Pawn on a7 (KRKPA7)'. Donated to UCI ML Repository on August 1, 1989.
sample_data.dataset_history: Developed by Alen Shapiro in 1983 as part of his Ph.D. thesis 'The Role of Structured Induction in Expert Systems' at University of Edinburgh. Used to demonstrate structured induction methodology for extracting expert knowledge. The endgame was chosen as it was difficult enough to challenge master players but tractable for analysis. Became a standard UCI benchmark dataset.
sample_data.inference_notes: The exact semantic meanings of all 36 attributes are documented in Shapiro's 1987 book 'Structured Induction in Expert Systems' (Addison-Wesley) but this source is not readily available digitally. The attribute names follow clear patterns: 'bk' prefix for black king features, 'wk' for white king, 'r' for rook-related features. Many attributes encode chess concepts like opposition, zugzwang, skewer tactics, and control of key squares. The binary encoding (t/f) simplifies complex positional judgments. Some attributes like 'bkxwp' and 'rkxwp' reference white pawns that don't exist in this endgame, suggesting these may be generalized features from a broader chess encoding system.
